                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d872">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">121.5561/79: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Kuibyshev</hi> (<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >Moscow</hi>)</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1942-01-03T12:00:00+03:00">January 3,
                        1942—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 10:03 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6. Department’s 1303, December 20, [1941,] 3 p.m. A note has been received from
                    the Foreign Office stating, in response to the Embassy’s communication regarding
                    Lieutenant Taecker, that “the competent Soviet authorities have no objection to
                    the assignment of Lieutenant C. H. Taecker as Assistant Naval Attaché to the
                    Embassy in Kuibyshev and deem it possible to allow him a temporary stay in
                    Vladivostok with observance of the conditions stipulated in the above mentioned
                    note of the Embassy.”</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Thurston</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
